						<div class="postbody">I'm still not sure what you mean. No matter the sprite size, you loose 9 sprites out of 64, with 55 remaining which means you loose 14% of your sprites. Them being 8x8 or 8x16 doesn't affect this. On the other side you loose twice the area with 8x16 sprites because you're loosing sprites twice as big (but you had more sprite to start with).<br /><br />If what you mean is that in a game with the same graphics, you are less likely to hit the 64 sprites bar with 8x16 sprite than with 8x8 I agree, so of course this remain true when the bar is lowered to 55. Nothing new here. However, it's not as simple as a calulation of area. For example, if you want to draw a 4x4 pixel bullet, you'll have to use a full 8x16 sprite if you use 8x16 sprites.</div>

